               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18180114-151-person1071">
                  JOHN 
                  CROSS
               <interp inst="t18180114-151-person1071" type="surname" value="CROSS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180114-151-person1071" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180114-151-person1071" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a patrol of Bow-street. I met the prisoner at Ball's-pond Common, on the 30th of December, about five o'clock in the evening, with a bundle. I asked him what it was? he said it was his clothes, which he had brought from Mr. Kershaw's; that he had been painting the house, and slept in the stable while he was there. I took him back to Mr. Kershaw's, who claimed the bundle.</p>
               <p>ULYSSE HARRISSON. I am servant to Mr. Kershaw. The prisoner was not employed about the house.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18180114-151-person1072">
                  WILLIAM 
                  KERSHAW
               <interp inst="t18180114-151-person1072" type="surname" value="KERSHAW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180114-151-person1072" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180114-151-person1072" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at Newington Green. The things were in my stable for the use of my groom, who slept over it-the prisoner is his brother. The stable was broken open. (Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I found them.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18180114-151-verdict813" type="verdictDescription">
